%%TITLE
Prevalence of human papillomavirus in oropharyngeal cancer: a multicenter study in Japan.
%%ABSTRACT
The incidence rates of oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC) have risen steadily in the USA and in northern Europe. These increases are thought to be a consequence of persistent infection with high-risk human papillomavirus (HPV) in OPSCC patients. HPV is an emerging etiologic factor in OPSCC. In Japan, the incidence of OPSCC has significantly increased over the last three decades. However, the population of HPV-positive OPSCC patients is currently unknown. We examined the nationwide trends with regard to HPV incidence in OPSCC patients at 21 specific sites, and examined the relationship between the presence of HPV and survival in OPSCC patients in Japan.Tumor samples were obtained from patients with OPSCC prior to treatment, and HPV infection was investigated by polymerase chain reaction (PCR). Hybrid Capture 2 (HC2) was also adopted for swab examination on the surface of fresh tumors.HPV was detected by PCR in 79 (50.3%) out of 157 OPSCC patients. The clinical features of HPV-positive OPSCC were low differentiation, a tendency to involve the lateral wall, and high nodal staging. The sensitivity and specificity of HC2 were 93.7 and 96.2%, respectively, indicating its utility as a screening test. HPV-positive patients had significantly better overall survival and disease-free survival than HPV-negative patients.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patients
Twenty-one institutes belonging to the Basic Research Cooperative Group of Head and Neck Cancer participated in this study. This prospective cohort study was approved by the Institutional Review Board of each institute. All of the patients provided written informed consent. Between September 2008 and August 2010, 157 patients with OPSCC were registered. Fresh samples were obtained from the primary site of patients prior to treatment. At the same time, samples for application to Hybrid Capture 2 (HC2) technology were obtained by scrubbing an examination brush on the surface of the tumor. After these examinations, patients at each institute were treated with surgery or chemoradiotherapy (CRT). Clinical information was obtained from the clinical and surgical charts. The tumor-node-metastasis (TNM) classification and stage were determined according to the 6th UICC TNM classification and stage groupings. Information about patients was sent to the National Tokyo Medical Center. Treatment was performed at each institute without any information regarding HPV status. Each institute was blind to the results of HPV detection to avoid selection bias for the treatment method.
Tumor Samples
In each case, after histological confirmation of squamous cell carcinoma with hematoxylin and eosin staining, tissue samples from the primary site were immediately sent to the SRL Laboratory (Hachioji, Tokyo, Japan), which is a clinical testing company with a nationwide network. DNA was extracted from the fresh tissue samples at the laboratory. DNA from each sample was sent to the National Tokyo Medical Center, and HPV detection and genotyping were performed by polymerase chain reaction (PCR). Scrub samples were sent to SRL, and high-risk HPV screening was performed using the HC2 method.
HPV Detection and Genotyping
Polymerase Chain Reaction
The detection of HPV types within the alpha-papillomavirus genera was performed by multiplex PCR using a TaKaRa Human Papillomavirus Typing Set (Takara Bio Inc. No. 6603) and Human Papillomavirus PCR Detection Set (Takara Bio Inc. No. 6602). The Takara Human Papillomavirus PCR Typing Set is designed for the identification of a broad range of HPV types using HPV type-specific PCR. The Human Papillomavirus PCR Typing Set uses two pairs of consensus primers that are designed to amplify the E6 and E7 homologous regions of HPV (228–268 bp). Malignant HPV16, 18, 33, 52b and 58 types are amplified using the HPVpU-1M/ HPVpU-2R primer pair, while benign HPV6 and 11 types are amplified using the HPVpU-31B/HPVpU-2R primer pair. Digestion of the PCR products by restriction enzymes AccI, AfaI, AvaI, AvaII and BglII, available as Enzyme Set A, followed by agarose gel electrophoresis was used to identify the resident HPV types. The Human Papillomavirus PCR Detection Set offers a set of primers designed for the detection of HPV16, 18 and
33. These HPV types have all been detected in cervical carcinoma. This HPV PCR primer set allows simple and sensitive detection of HPV16, 18 and 33 through the amplification of viral DNA. Included in this set are specific amplification primers for the E6 region of HPV16, 18 and 33. Amplification product sizes are 140 bp for HPV16 and 18 and 141 bp for HPV33. The samples were reported as HPV-positive if any of the high-risk HPV DNA types (types 16, 18, 26, 31, 33, 35, 52, and 58) were detected.
Hybrid Capture 2
Detection of HPV via a screening test using HC2 technology was performed. This involves an in vitro nucleic acid hybridization microplate assay with signal amplification using microplate chemiluminescence for the qualitative detection of 13 high-risk types of HPV (types 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, and 68). Specimen DNA was denatured into single-stranded DNA by the addition of a denaturation solution and then hybridized with high-risk HPV-specific RNA probes. Negative and positive calibrators were used for quality control, according to the manufacturer’s instructions, by radioimmunoassay at the SRL Laboratory.
Statistical Analysis
Student’s t test, the χ2 test and Fisher’s test were used to evaluate differences in the patient character- istics after stratification by HPV status. The disease-free survival curve end point is defined by recurrence (local relapse, new lymph node metastasis or distant metastasis) during follow-up. All patients were observed within 2 months after surgery, and patients were periodically (every 0.5–2 months) examined on an outpa- tient basis to make sure they had not relapsed. Examinations consisted of standard tests, including endoscopy

and computed tomography of the chest and neck. Recurrence was established when a carcinoma was detected again in a primary tumor and cervical lymph node, or when distant metastases were observed by computed tomography. Disease-free survival curves were generated using the Kaplan-Meier method and compared using log-rank tests. Cox proportional hazard models were fitted for multivariate analysis adjusting for age, gender, smoking status, and HPV mutational status. Adjusted hazard ratios (HRs) and 95% confidence intervals (CIs) were also calculated. All of the statistical analyses were performed using Stata 9.1 (Stata Corp., College Station, Tex., USA). A p value <0.05 was considered statistically significant.
